# Test node-style subpath imports (package.json 'imports') with lazy indexing
# AND recursion disabled (-index=lazy -r=false lib/pkg). Only //lib/pkg is
# (re)generated; every other package keeps its committed BUILD file and is only
# reached if //lib/pkg asks gazelle to lazily index it.
#
# The npm_package target is disabled (see lib/pkg/BUILD.in) so the '#' subpath
# imports are resolved purely from the source ts_project. Under lazy indexing
# the '#sub' and '#internal/*' target directories (lib/pkg/sub, lib/pkg/internal)
# are only indexed when //lib/pkg declares them in GenerateResult.RelsToIndex,
# so resolution must expand the package.json 'imports' targets into
# rels-to-index (tsPackageInfoToRelsToIndex). Without that the imports resolve
# to "unknown js dependency".
# https://nodejs.org/api/packages.html#subpath-imports
#
#  * '#sub' -> ./sub/main.js resolves to //lib/pkg/sub
#  * '#ext' -> @lib/other resolves to :node_modules/@lib/other (pnpm, not index)
#  * '#internal/*' -> ./internal/*.js resolves '#internal/util' to //lib/pkg/internal
#  * '#~db' (odd alias) -> ./db/client.js resolves to //lib/pkg/db, a dependency
#    reached ONLY via the 'imports' field
workspace(name = "pnpm_workspace_imports_lazy_norecurse")
